PHASE C — CODE COVERAGE
========================

Step C1: Enable coverage in Xcode.
  In Xcode:
    Product → Scheme → Edit Scheme (or Cmd+<)
    → Test → Options tab
    → Check "Gather coverage for" → "All targets" (or select AITest target)
    → Close

Step C2: Run tests with coverage via xcodebuild (from Terminal, not sandbox):

  xcodebuild test \
    -scheme SmartInventory \
    -destination 'platform=iOS Simulator,name=iPhone 17 Pro Max,OS=latest' \
    -enableCodeCoverage YES \
    -resultBundlePath build/TestResults.xcresult \
    2>&1 | tee build/xcodebuild_coverage.log

Step C3: View coverage in Xcode.
  - Open Xcode → Report Navigator (Cmd+9) → select the latest test run
  - Click "Coverage" tab
  - Review coverage % per file

Step C4: Generate a coverage summary (optional CLI approach):
  xcrun xccov view --report build/TestResults.xcresult > build/coverage_report.txt
  cat build/coverage_report.txt | grep -E "(AITest/|\.swift)" | sort -t'%' -k1 -rn | head -40

Step C5: Identify low-coverage areas and report back.
  Files likely to have low coverage:
  - AITest/Views/SmartCountView.swift — no UI tests yet
  - AITest/Views/VoiceInventoryView.swift — no UI tests yet
  - AITest/Views/ImageInventoryView.swift — no UI tests yet
  - AITest/Views/PaperInventoryView.swift — no UI tests yet
  - AITest/Services/AnalyticsManager.swift — new, untested
  - AITest/Models/TeamManager.swift — team features

  For each file below 40% coverage, note it in automation_results.rtf with
  the coverage % and a recommendation for additional tests.

Step C6: Update automation_results.rtf with:
  - Total coverage % across all targets
  - Per-file breakdown for files above and below 50%
  - List of new flows added (81–87) and their pass/fail status
  - List of flows fixed in Phase A and what was changed

